TY  - CONF
TI  - Advanced Quad-Port Memory Design Featuring Dynamic Access Prioritization and Write Control
AU  - M. D. K
AU  - R. Verma
AU  - L. Shrinivasan
T2  - 2025 Control Instrumentation System Conference (CISCON)
AB  - The goal of this paper is to design and verify a Quad-Port Memory system with dynamic priority control using SystemVerilog. Traditional dual-port memories often run into issues when multiple accesses happen at the same time, which can slow down performance. To solve this, we've designed a memory system that supports simultaneous read and write operations on four independent ports. This not only boosts throughput but also improves scalability and overall memory efficiency. To manage conflicts during write operations, we've included a Dynamic Priority Control Unit. We've also added a Write Restriction Mechanism to prevent unauthorized access to critical memory areas. A SystemVerilog-based testbench has been created to test the design across different scenarios, checking its functionality, how it handles priorities, and how well it controls access. with better support for concurrent access and reduced contention, this design improves system performance and is a strong fit for multi-core processors, embedded systems, and real-time applications.
