AB  - Low-frequency (e.g., 0.5–1.5 GHz) microwave radiometry is expected to enhance the observation capability such as for sea ice thickness. One of the most important issues to realize the low-frequency microwave observation is to remove radio-frequency interference (RFI) in real time. To achieve this, we are developing a digital processor, which is an essential component for RFI removal, for ground-based low-frequency microwave radiometer based on the software-defined radio concept. We implemented fast-Fourier transform, data integration, and RFI removal processing on FPGA and evaluated the function. Cross-frequency and kurtosis detection methods were implemented as the RFI removal function. All functions worked as expected, and we verified that RFI removal processing was possible. In the future, we plan to combine the digital processor and the frontend unit, and improve both RFI removal methods.
