AU  - Y. Fan
AU  - C. -T. Chen
AU  - K. -Y. Lai
AU  - H. -P. Lu
AU  - X. -Y. Ou
AU  - Y. -X. Huang
AU  - Q. -J. Feng
AU  - R. -J. Cao
T2  - 2025 7th International Conference on Electronic Engineering and Informatics (EEI)
AB  - With the rapid global deployment of 5G, the number of IoT devices is expected to increase explosively in the coming years. However, the widespread adoption of IoT also brings many risks, such as vulnerabilities, attacks, and device control. When combined with 5G, these risks are magnified, posing a severe challenge to the security of 5G networks. To address this challenge, it is necessary to deeply understand the vulnerabilities of the 5G system, especially the IoT part, and explore the composition of IoT devices and their interaction with 5G infrastructure. According to Huawei's “5G System Security White Paper”, many IoT devices use untrusted components, which are exposed to public networks and are vulnerable to attacks, threatening the security of 5G networks. At the same time as 5G and IoT integrate to facilitate life, new risks are emerging. To ensure the stability and security of 5G networks, comprehensive protection measures must be strengthened. Strategies such as using strong passwords, limiting default credentials, changing SSH keys, and disabling remote port services should be adopted at the IoT end. The network layer and wireless access network also need to be defended to ensure that only authorized devices can access the network. Only through comprehensive protective measures can we ensure that IoT devices will not become targets of network attacks, thereby guaranteeing the security and stability of 5G networks.
