AU  - B. Pang
AU  - H. Li
T2  - 2021 6th International Conference on Transportation Information and Safety (ICTIS)
AB  - Reducing energy use and greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions is now a major policy goal for most ports. Fossil fuel combustion is the main source of GHG emissions. To ingrain decarbonation and energy conservation of ports, the use of innovative technology appears as a critical conduit. In this context, this paper conducts a review of the application of realtime energy consumption monitoring system in ports aiming at pointing out the problems existing in the development of China's ports energy monitoring system. Our systematic review shows that there is a great potential for ports to achieve energy consumption intelligent data analysis, energy use trend prediction and energy saving potential mining analysis. We make suggestions for improvement of real-time monitoring and management system. The establishment of the system can not only improve the accuracy of energy statistics and GHG emission monitoring, but also enhance the digitalization of ports.
