TY  - CONF
TI  - Live Detection and Mitigation for SSH Brute Force Attacks
AU  - N. Zahreldine
AU  - A. Jaber
AU  - A. H. El Fawal
AU  - D. M. Bleik
AU  - A. Mansour
T2  - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Emerging Trends in Engineering and Computing (ETECOM)
AB  - Secure Shell (SSH) is a critical remote management protocol, but its pervasiveness makes it a prime target for brute-force, scan, and exploitation attacks. Conventional defenses such as static firewall rules or post-malicious-event log analysis are often reactive and can be easily bypassed. The aim of this paper is to provide an efficient, multi-layered defense system for securing SSH services on Ubuntu servers based on both proactive and reactive mechanisms. The proposed architecture combines NFtables-based hardening of the base image, Port Knocking to obscure the SSH port from scanners without legitimate access, and automated countermeasures using Fail2Ban and IPTables rate limiting. At its very core, a lightweight Python detection module employs PyShark to perform live packet inspection, facilitating early pattern detection in seconds. The system was validated in a controlled testbed setup using Kali Linux as the attacking host. Simulations indicate that an unprotected server left alone was compromised within a second, while the proposed framework successfully detected and countered attacks in real-time. The solution offers an adaptive, adaptive, and resource-efficient approach to improving SSH security against emerging threats.
